objectives:

    The knowledge of family laws is important for lawyers. This course is designed to endow the students with knowledge of both the codified and uncodified portions of Mohammedan Law. The course concerns itself with the sources, schools, institutions, succession, maintenance, menace of dowry, etc. In addition the students have to familiarize themselves with the provisions of the Indian Succession Act.

unit 1:
    Development of Islamic Law: Advent of Islam & development of Muslim Law, Schools of Islamic Law, Who's is a Mohammaden; Conversion and its consequences on family: Marriage, Guardianship, Succession; Child and Family: the Shariat Act, 1937; Sources of Islamic Law; Concept of Marriage: Definition, object, nature, essential requirements of a Muslim marriage, classification of marriage - Legal effects of valid, void and irregular marriage - Muta marriage; Customary practices and State regulation: Polygamy; Child marriage; .Option of Puberty; Dower; Kinds of Dower: Dower when confirmed; Widow's Right of Retention

unit 2:
    Parentage Legitimacy, and Acknowledgement of Paternity Custody, Maintenance and education, Guardianship and parental rights. Matrimonial Remedies under Islamic Law and Indian Divorce Act, 1869(Amended Act) – Modes of Talak – Effects of Talak – Iddat - Nullity of marriage - Bar to matrimonial relief; Alimony and Maintenance: Alimony and Maintenance as an independent remedy- A review under Muslim law, Indian Divorce Act,1869, provisions under the Criminal Procedure Code, 1973; Maintenance of divorced Muslim Women under the Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986.

unit 3:
    Will-Meaning, Limitations on a Mohammaden in making a will; Difference between will and gift, Will made in death bed or during illness; Gifts(Hiba) : Essentials of Valid Gift; Kinds of Hiba; Revocation of Gifts; Wakf; Essentials of valid Wakf: Mutawalli – Appointment – Powers and Duties of Mutawalli; Law relating Pre-emption; Nature of Right of Pre-emption; Who can Pre-empt; Formalities; When the Right of Pre-emption is lost.

unit 4:
    Muslim law of Inheritance- Shia and Sunni schools; Distribution of property under Indian Succession Act of 1925(Of Christians, Parsis)- Domicile- Kinds of Domicile – Modes of acquisition of Domicile; Parsis Intestate succession and Non Parsis Intestate succession, Succession certificate, Probate and letters of administration, Powers and Duties of Executor.

unit 5:
    Wills – Privileged and unprivileged wills - Construction of Wills in brief - Void bequests, void wills, Kinds of Legacies; Specific and Demonstrative Legacy; Ademption of Legacies; - Protection of property of the deceased; Appointment of Curator – Powers and Duties Family Courts Act, 1984- Constitution, powers, and its functions; Need for Uniform Civil Code- Article 44 of Indian Constitution.

books prescribed:
    Mulla, Principles of Mohammedan Law,(New Delhi: Lexis Nexis, 1906).
    Paras Diwan , Law of Intestate and Testamentary Succession, 4th Edition, (New Delhi: Universal Law Publishing Co. Ltd, 2013)

reference books:
    B. B. Mitra ,Indian Succession Act, 1925.15th Edition, (New Delhi: Jain Book Agency, 2013)
    A. A. A Fyzee, Outlines of Mohammedan Law, (Oxford University Press, 1974)
    Basu, N.D., Law of Succession, 5th Edition, (Calcutta: Eastern Law House, 1974)
    Paras Diwan, Family Law: Law of Marriage and Divorce in India, (New Delhi: Universal Law Publishing Co. Ltd, 2011)
    A. M. Bhattachargee, Muslim Law and the Constitution (Calcutta: Eastern Law House,1994)
    Tahir Mohamood, The Muslim Law of India, (Law Book Company, 1980)
    Indian Divorce Act, 1869 – Bare Act


questions:

    Unit 1 - Development of Islamic Law and Marriage

        Discuss the development of Islamic Law and explain the advent of Islam & development of Muslim Law. Examine the schools of Islamic Law and the concept of who is a Mohammaden with relevant case laws.

        Explain the concept of Marriage under Muslim Law. Discuss the definition, object, nature and essential requirements of a Muslim marriage with classification of marriage and legal effects of valid, void and irregular marriage.

        Critically analyse the customary practices and State regulation relating to Polygamy and Child marriage under Muslim Law. Examine the Option of Puberty, Dower and Kinds of Dower with leading judicial pronouncements.

    Unit 2 - Legitimacy, Custody and Matrimonial Remedies

        Explain the concepts of Parentage, Legitimacy and Acknowledgement of Paternity under Muslim Law. Discuss Custody, Maintenance, education and Guardianship with relevant case laws.

        Examine the Matrimonial Remedies under Islamic Law and Indian Divorce Act, 1869. Discuss the Modes of Talak, Effects of Talak, Iddat and Nullity of marriage with leading judicial interpretations.

        Critically analyse the provisions relating to Alimony and Maintenance under Muslim law, Indian Divorce Act 1869, Criminal Procedure Code 1973 and Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986 with relevant case laws.

    Unit 3 - Wills, Gifts and Wakf

        Discuss the limitations on a Mohammaden in making a will. Distinguish between will and gift under Muslim Law. Examine Will made in death bed or during illness with relevant judicial pronouncements.

        Explain the concept of Gifts (Hiba) under Muslim Law. Discuss the essentials of Valid Gift, Kinds of Hiba and Revocation of Gifts with leading case laws.

        Critically examine the provisions relating to Wakf under Muslim Law. Discuss the essentials of valid Wakf, Mutawalli's appointment, powers and duties, and the law relating to Pre-emption with relevant judicial interpretations.

    Unit 4 - Law of Inheritance and Succession

        Explain the Muslim law of Inheritance under Shia and Sunni schools. Discuss the distribution of property with relevant case laws.

        Examine the provisions relating to distribution of property under Indian Succession Act of 1925. Discuss Domicile, Kinds of Domicile and Modes of acquisition of Domicile with leading judicial pronouncements.

        Critically analyse the provisions relating to Parsis Intestate succession and Non Parsis Intestate succession. Discuss Succession certificate, Probate, letters of administration and Powers and Duties of Executor with relevant case laws.

    Unit 5 - Wills, Legacies and Family Courts

        Distinguish between Privileged and unprivileged wills. Discuss the Construction of Wills, Void bequests and void wills with relevant judicial interpretations.

        Examine the provisions relating to Kinds of Legacies, Specific and Demonstrative Legacy and Ademption of Legacies. Discuss Protection of property of the deceased and Appointment of Curator with leading case laws.

        Critically analyse the provisions of Family Courts Act, 1984. Discuss the Constitution, powers and functions of Family Courts and examine the Need for Uniform Civil Code under Article 44 of Indian Constitution with relevant judicial pronouncements.
